# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: andrew-tyler
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:andrew-tyler/a-cow-at-my-table] It covers the conflict between animal rights advocates and the meat industry, and their respective attempts to influence consumers.
[src:andrew-tyler/a-cow-at-my-table] It was directed, shot, and edited by Jennifer Abbott, who spent five years travelling across Canada, the United States, Australia and New Zealand to interview representatives on all sides.
[src:andrew-tyler/a-cow-at-my-table] The film intercuts these interviews with images of farm animals and industrial farming operations.
[src:andrew-tyler/a-cow-at-my-table] It explores what is sometimes popularly called factory farming.
[src:andrew-tyler/a-cow-at-my-table] The filming of *A Cow at My Table* drew early criticism from the Canadian meat industry, with both the Ontario Chicken Marketing Board and the Dairy Farmers of Ontario publishing articles warning of Abbott's actions.
[src:andrew-tyler/a-cow-at-my-table] Music for the film was performed by Oh Susanna.
[src:andrew-tyler/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] Salt was active in a number of reform causes in the late 19th century, including prison reform, education, socialism, and animal protection.
[src:andrew-tyler/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] He later founded the Humanitarian League in 1891.
[src:andrew-tyler/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] In *A Plea for Vegetarianism and Other Essays*, he argued that a vegetarian diet was humane, economical, and practicable, and challenged common objections to abstention from meat.
[src:andrew-tyler/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] Across these essays, Salt defends vegetarianism on ethical, social, and economic grounds.
[src:andrew-tyler/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] He argues against the killing of animals for food, disputes the view that meat is necessary for health, and links diet to wider questions of conduct and social reform.
[src:andrew-tyler/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] Several essays also attack blood sports and reply to objections made by critics of vegetarianism, including Sir Henry Thompson.
[src:andrew-tyler/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] Themes developed in *A Plea for Vegetarianism and Other Essays* appeared again in Salt's later writings, including *Animals' Rights: Considered in Relation to Social Progress* (1892).
[src:andrew-tyler/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] At a social meeting organised by the London Vegetarian Society on 20 November 1931, Gandhi said that Salt's *A Plea for Vegetarianism* had shown him that vegetarianism was "a moral duty" and not only a matter of custom or personal vow.
[src:andrew-tyler/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Robert Morris (1703–1754) was an English writer on architecture.
[src:andrew-tyler/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] His published works include *Lectures on Architecture* (1734–36), *An Essay on Harmony* (1739), and *The Art of Architecture* (1742).
[src:andrew-tyler/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] He also wrote poems, essays, and pamphlets, and worked as a surveyor.
[src:andrew-tyler/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] According to Adams, Morris encountered *A Dissertation on the Voluntary Eating of Blood* in 1745.
[src:andrew-tyler/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Expecting an argument against flesh-eating, he instead found a defence of meat consumption based on a post-Flood reading of Genesis.
[src:andrew-tyler/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Morris disagreed with that interpretation and wrote a reply, which was published in 1746 as *A Reasonable Plea for the Animal Creation*.
[src:andrew-tyler/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] The treatise is made up of a preface, a letter to General Foliot, nine letters addressed to a friend, and a concluding reply to *A Dissertation on the Voluntary Eating of Blood*.
[src:andrew-tyler/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Adams writes that the central part of the book consists of letters Morris had written in 1737 and 1738 and later incorporated into the printed work.
[src:andrew-tyler/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Morris argues that humans have no natural right to kill animals for food.
[src:andrew-tyler/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] He appeals both to Genesis and to "the nature and reason of things", maintaining that the food originally given to humans was the produce of the earth.
[src:andrew-tyler/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] He rejects attempts to justify meat-eating through scripture, custom, bodily necessity, or animal predation.
[src:andrew-tyler/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] He also argues that humans are not naturally fitted for carnivory, and describes butchery and cookery as artificial practices rather than natural ones.
[src:andrew-tyler/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Drawing on writers such as Pythagoras and Plutarch, he attributes feeling and a degree of rationality to animals and treats their destruction for food as a matter of cruelty and injustice.
[src:andrew-tyler/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] In her introduction to the 2005 republication, Carol J.
[src:andrew-tyler/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Adams describes the treatise as a neglected contribution to 18th-century vegetarian and animal-ethical writing.
[src:andrew-tyler/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] She argues that Morris' case against flesh-eating is centred less on health than on moral obligation, and that his appeal to the "light of Nature" gives the work a distinctive place among early vegetarian texts.
[src:andrew-tyler/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Adams also comments on the book's epistolary form, noting that its letters are addressed to a flesh-eating friend.
[src:andrew-tyler/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] She treats that structure as part of the book's argument, since Morris repeatedly answers objections and defends vegetarianism against the assumptions of a meat-eating society.
[src:andrew-tyler/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] She further notes Morris' rejection of claims of human superiority and his attribution of sentience and reason to animals.
[src:andrew-tyler/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] On Adams' reading, these features connect the treatise to later debates in animal ethics.
[src:andrew-tyler/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Before its republication in 2005, the treatise had appeared only occasionally in modern writing.
[src:andrew-tyler/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Whisker, John Simons, and Rod Preece each referred to it as an early contribution to vegetarian and animal-ethical thought.
[src:andrew-tyler/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Simons described Morris, together with John Hildrop, as a precursor to Humphry Primatt.
[src:andrew-tyler/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Preece quoted from the treatise and placed Morris among earlier writers who argued for vegetarianism on ethical grounds, including John Oswald, George Nicholson, Joseph Ritson, and John Frank Newton.
[src:andrew-tyler/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] In 2005, the treatise was republished in *Organization & Environment* with an introductory article by Carol J.
[src:andrew-tyler/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] Francis Hutcheson (1694–1746) was a philosopher of the Scottish Enlightenment and professor of moral philosophy at the University of Glasgow.
[src:andrew-tyler/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] He was a leading defender of moral sense theory, according to which moral judgement arises from an innate sense rather than from reason alone.
[src:andrew-tyler/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] He began work on *A System of Moral Philosophy* in 1738 and continued revising it until his death.
[src:andrew-tyler/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] In *A System of Moral Philosophy*, Hutcheson sets out a broad account of ethics, natural law, private rights, and political society.
[src:andrew-tyler/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] The first book concerns human nature and the supreme good.
[src:andrew-tyler/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] Hutcheson discusses the faculties of the mind, the affections, and the will, and restates his view that human beings possess a moral sense by which they approve virtue and disapprove vice.
[src:andrew-tyler/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] He argues that virtue is grounded in benevolence directed by reason, and relates moral life to providence and natural religion.
[src:andrew-tyler/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] The second book deals with natural law and private rights.
[src:andrew-tyler/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] Hutcheson discusses obligation, contracts, property, promises, oaths, and legal duties.
[src:andrew-tyler/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] He distinguishes between perfect and imperfect rights, and treats justice as distinct from broader duties of benevolence.
[src:andrew-tyler/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] He also argues that laws should answer to reason, public good, and natural equity.
[src:andrew-tyler/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] The third book turns to civil society and government.
[src:andrew-tyler/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] Hutcheson examines the basis of political authority, the forms of government, and topics including marriage, family, slavery, taxation, magistracy, war, and civil law.
[src:andrew-tyler/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] He holds that political power must be exercised for the common good and with the consent of the governed.
[src:andrew-tyler/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] Modern commentators have drawn attention to Hutcheson's discussion of animals in the *System*.
[src:andrew-tyler/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] In a 2007 article, Aaron Garrett argued that Hutcheson offered an early argument for animal rights by grounding moral consideration in sentience and the capacity to suffer rather than in rational agency alone.
[src:andrew-tyler/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] Garrett also compared Hutcheson's treatment of animals with his discussion of infants, and placed him in a line of thought distinct from Lockean rights theory.
[src:andrew-tyler/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] Michael Bradie likewise noted that Hutcheson treated cruelty to animals as morally wrong because animals are capable of suffering.
[src:andrew-tyler/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] At the same time, Bradie argued that Hutcheson retained a hierarchical account in which human beings, because of their superior rational capacities, may use animals when necessary.
[src:andrew-tyler/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] Bradie described this position as an early attempt to balance human interests with concern for animal suffering.
[src:andrew-tyler/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] Foulis in Glasgow and distributed in London by A.
[src:andrew-tyler/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] It appeared in two volumes in 1755, five years after Hutcheson's death; it was published posthumously by his son Francis Hutcheson the younger, from the original manuscript.
[src:andrew-tyler/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] A new edition was published in 2000 by Thoemmes, with an introduction by Daniel Carey, and was later republished by A & C Black in 2006.
[src:andrew-tyler/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] A further edition was issued by Cambridge University Press in 2015.
[src:andrew-tyler/abandoned-pets] Animal welfare laws in many states of the United States make it a crime to abandon a pet.
[src:andrew-tyler/abandoned-pets] Often, when abandoned, pets are forced to fend for themselves and become stray or feral.
[src:andrew-tyler/abandoned-pets] Feral cats are said to outnumber feral dogs and can become challenging to handle and socialize enough to be re-introduced to a new human owner.
[src:andrew-tyler/abandoned-pets] In general, only some newly abandoned cats and very young feral kittens can be tamed.
[src:andrew-tyler/abandoned-pets] There is a necessity to investigate interventions to prevent companion-animal relinquishment.
[src:andrew-tyler/abandoned-pets] Stray animals increase potential exposure to zoonotic diseases like rabies.
[src:andrew-tyler/abandoned-pets] Cat bites or scratches involving stray or feral animals are eight times more common than dog bites.
[src:andrew-tyler/abandoned-pets] The impacts of dog and cat predation on wildlife can also be significant.
[src:andrew-tyler/abandoned-pets] Some pets relinquished to an animal shelter will be euthanized due to a lack of space or financial resources.
[src:andrew-tyler/abandoned-pets] Millions of companion animals enter animal shelters every year in the United States.
[src:andrew-tyler/abandoned-pets] However, the number of dogs and cats euthanized in US shelters declined from approximately 2.6 million in 2011 to 1.5 million in 2018.
[src:andrew-tyler/abandoned-pets] This decline can be partially explained by an increase in the percentage of animals adopted, and an increase in the number of stray animals successfully returned to their owners.
[src:andrew-tyler/abandoned-pets] Studies show that the majority of people who relinquish an animal also report being emotionally attached to the animal.
[src:andrew-tyler/abandoned-pets] It has been reported that when forced to abandon their animals in an evacuation, people suffer mental issues such as grief, depression, and post-traumatic stress disorder.
[src:andrew-tyler/abandoned-pets] Recognizing the importance of pets to their owners and their role in public health is an essential first step in improving a public health problem that has been seen repeatedly in the past and is unlikely to change in the future.
[src:andrew-tyler/abandoned-pets] Pet abandonment increased during the 2008 financial crisis.
[src:andrew-tyler/abandoned-pets] In early 2009, the ASPCA published advice for people facing foreclosure and the loss of their pets, recommending finding a foster or adoption situation for your pet, being aware of rental property rules for pets, and checking with animal shelters and animal rescue groups.
[src:andrew-tyler/abolitionism-animal-rights] Abolitionists disagree on the strategy that must be used to achieve their goal.
[src:andrew-tyler/abolitionism-animal-rights] Abolitionists such as Steven Best and David Nibert argue, respectively, that embracing alliance politics and militant direct action for change (including civil disobedience, mass confrontation, etc), and transcending capitalism are integral to ending animal exploitation.
[src:andrew-tyler/abolitionism-animal-rights] Abolitionists generally oppose movements that seek to make animal use more humane or to abolish specific forms of animal use, since they believe this undermines the movement to abolish all forms of animal use.
[src:andrew-tyler/abolitionism-animal-rights] The objective is to secure a moral and legal paradigm shift, whereby animals are no longer regarded as things to be owned and used.
[src:andrew-tyler/abolitionism-animal-rights] The American philosopher Tom Regan writes that abolitionists want empty cages, not bigger ones.
[src:andrew-tyler/abolitionism-animal-rights] This is contrasted with animal welfare, which seeks incremental reform, and animal protectionism, which seeks to combine the first principles of abolitionism with an incremental approach, but which is regarded by some abolitionists as another form of welfarism or "New Welfarism".
[src:andrew-tyler/abolitionism-animal-rights] The word relates to the historical term abolitionism—a social movement to end slavery or human ownership of other humans.
[src:andrew-tyler/abolitionism-animal-rights] Based on the way of evaluating welfare reforms, abolitionists can be either radical or pragmatic.
[src:andrew-tyler/abolitionism-animal-rights] While the former maintain that welfare reforms can only be dubiously described as moral improvements, the latter consider welfare reforms as moral improvements even when the conditions they permit are unjust.
[src:andrew-tyler/abolitionism-animal-rights] He calls such groups the "new welfarists", arguing that, though their aim is an end to animal use, the reforms they pursue are indistinguishable from reforms agreeable to traditional welfarists, who he says have no interest in abolishing animal use.
[src:andrew-tyler/abolitionism-animal-rights] He argues that reform campaigns entrench the property status of animals, and validate the view that animals simply need to be treated better.
[src:andrew-tyler/abolitionism-animal-rights] Instead, he writes, the public's view that animals can be used and consumed ought to be challenged.
[src:andrew-tyler/abolitionism-animal-rights] His position is that this should be done by promoting ethical veganism.
[src:andrew-tyler/abolitionism-animal-rights] Others think that this should be done by creating a public debate in society.
[src:andrew-tyler/abolitionism-animal-rights] He rhetorically asks, how can one hope to create some consumer base for this new vegan world when over a billion people live on less than a dollar a day?
[src:andrew-tyler/abolitionism-animal-rights] Nibert acknowledges that post-capitalism on its own will not automatically end animal exploitation or bring about a more just world, but that it is a "necessary precondition" for such changes.
[src:andrew-tyler/abolitionism-animal-rights] New welfarists argue that there is no logical or practical contradiction between abolitionism and "welfarism".
[src:andrew-tyler/abolitionism-animal-rights] Welfarists think that they can be working toward abolition, but by gradual steps, pragmatically taking into account what most people can be realistically persuaded to do in the short as well as the long term, and reduce animal suffering as it is most urgent to relieve.
[src:andrew-tyler/abolitionism-animal-rights] People for the Ethical Treatment of Animals, for example, in addition to promoting local improvements in the treatment of animals, promote vegetarianism.
[src:andrew-tyler/abolitionism-animal-rights] Although some people believe that changing the legal status of nonhuman sentient beings is a first step in abolishing ownership or mistreatment, others argue that this will not succeed if the consuming public has not already begun to reduce or eliminate its exploitation of animals for food.
[src:andrew-tyler/abolitionism-animal-rights] In 1992, Switzerland amended its constitution to recognize animals as *beings* and not *things*.
[src:andrew-tyler/abolitionism-animal-rights] The dignity of animals is also protected in Switzerland.
[src:andrew-tyler/abolitionism-animal-rights] New Zealand granted basic rights to five great ape species in 1999.
[src:andrew-tyler/abolitionism-animal-rights] Their use is now forbidden in research, testing or teaching.
[src:andrew-tyler/abolitionism-animal-rights] Germany added animal welfare in a 2002 amendment to its constitution, becoming the first European Union member to do so.
[src:andrew-tyler/abolitionism-animal-rights] In 2007, the parliament of the Balearic Islands, an autonomous province of Spain, passed the world's first legislation granting legal rights to all great apes.
[src:andrew-tyler/abolitionism-animal-rights] In 2013, India officially recognized dolphins as non-human persons.
[src:andrew-tyler/abolitionism-animal-rights] In 2014, France revised the legal status of animals from movable property to sentient beings.
[src:andrew-tyler/abolitionism-animal-rights] In 2015, the province of Quebec in Canada adopted the Animal Welfare and Safety Act, which gave animals the legal status of "sentient beings with biological needs".
[src:andrew-tyler/adam-gottlieb-weigen] Weigan was the son of a surgeon and was born at Waiblingen in 1677.
[src:andrew-tyler/adam-gottlieb-weigen] He studied theology at Württemberg but also took interest in anatomy and natural science.
[src:andrew-tyler/adam-gottlieb-weigen] Weigen became a pastor and advocate of pietism in Leonberg.
[src:andrew-tyler/adam-gottlieb-weigen] Weigan was influenced by the writings of Philipp Spener.
[src:andrew-tyler/adam-gottlieb-weigen] Weigen argued for a compassionate treatment of the animals from a Christian theological framework.
[src:andrew-tyler/adam-gottlieb-weigen] In 1711, Weigen authored *De Jure Hominis in Creaturas*.
[src:andrew-tyler/adam-gottlieb-weigen] It has been described as "the first work ever to deal with the topic of animal rights as a general theme." The book became known in Denmark and inspired Laurids Smith.
[src:andrew-tyler/adam-gottlieb-weigen] Weigen moved to Wahlheim, where he died in 1727.
[src:andrew-tyler/andrew-tyler] Tyler was born on 8 September 1946, in Hackney, London.
[src:andrew-tyler/andrew-tyler] He grew up in a Jewish children's home from the ages of six to fourteen, when he left school and worked his way up to being a junior reporter at *Drapers & Fashion Weekly*.
[src:andrew-tyler/andrew-tyler] Tyler wrote for *NME* from 1973 to 1980, interviewing several famous musicians including, Bruce Springsteen, Stevie Wonder, Ray Davies, Leonard Cohen and John Lennon.
[src:andrew-tyler/andrew-tyler] In the early 1980s, he was news feature editor for *Time Out*.
[src:andrew-tyler/andrew-tyler] He joined Animal Aid in 1995, later becoming director.
[src:andrew-tyler/andrew-tyler] Tyler married Sara Starkey in 1978, who had a son from a previous marriage.
[src:andrew-tyler/andrew-tyler] Near the end of his life, Tyler suffered from a degenerative back condition and Parkinson's disease.
[src:andrew-tyler/andrew-tyler] He retired in 2016 and finished his memoir *My Life As an Animal* (2017).
[src:andrew-tyler/andrew-tyler] For the final six weeks of his life, he recorded a video diary, in which he advocated for allowing people to die with dignity.
[src:andrew-tyler/andrew-tyler] Tyler ended his life at the Dignitas clinic in Switzerland, on 28 April 2017.
